{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":4318,"name":"","username":"devrich","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/d/ba9def/{size}.png","created_at":"2015-01-23T20:20:10.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIn my testing; I have made a model and I would like to ‚Äúadd‚Äù a geometry to be used specifically for ‚Äúphysics only‚Äù and I have a couple quesitons if I may?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn my model the idea is to have the physics be basically a cude or a sphere that would completely encapsulate the actual model inside it.  Think of those bouncing balls at toy stores that are clear and contain a colorful object inside:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eMyModel.mdl\n'----Outter-Most-Physics-Only-Geometry\n       '----Geometry1\n             '----Geometry2\n                   '----Geometry3\n                        '----Geometry_n\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e1:  How to tell Urho3D to use that specific ‚Äúphsics geometry‚Äù for the physics calculations? ( and \u003cem\u003eONLY\u003c/em\u003e use that specific geometry for physics calculations and \u003cem\u003enot\u003c/em\u003e use any other geometry in the .mdl ) ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e2:  I am thinking about setting a material to this ‚Äúphysics only‚Äù geometry to be 100% transparent ‚Äì but do i ‚Äòhave‚Äô to do that or should I just leave it with-out a material ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-i\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-u\"\u003eEdit:\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e  Essentially; I want ‚ÄúBullet Physics‚Äù to do it‚Äôs calculations on the outside object ( ball, box, capsule, whatever‚Ä¶ ) \u003cem\u003ebut\u003c/em\u003e have the ‚ÄúRenderer‚Äù render the inside geometry while ‚Äòignoring‚Äô the outside physics shape‚Ä¶ I hope i‚Äôm making sence because as normal and simple as this seems; i appear to be a little lost  \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/blush.png?v=5\" title=\":blush:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":blush:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-i\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-u\"\u003eEdit:\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e I mean is it something simple like just naming my ‚Äúphysics-only-geometry‚Äù something specific like ‚ÄúBulletPhysicsONLY‚Äù ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-u\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-i\"\u003eEdit:\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e Another way of looking at this is the idea that we could have say a ‚Äúghost‚Äù character and have ‚Äòonly‚Äô the hands, feet, and head ( these would all be separate geometries ) be detected by the physics system \u003cem\u003ebut\u003c/em\u003e leave the other parts not detected by the physics.  This sounds crazy but would actually make for a pretty good ghost game in which all your attacks go through the ghost character but when they hit or kick you ( or other objects ) then the physics reacts on you/the environment and if you hit them then the physics reacts on them‚Ä¶ You could even design such a ghost game that you ‚Äòhave‚Äô to destroy all the physics parts ( hands, feet, head ) to beat the character ( maybe a boss character )‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo I have some ideas ‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:02:54.654Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":10,"reads":5,"readers_count":4,"score":53.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":791,"topic_slug":"how-to-specify-a-specific-geometry-is-for-physics-only","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":188,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":4335,"name":"Justin Miller","username":"jmiller","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/jmiller/{size}/2367_2.png","created_at":"2015-01-24T15:42:17.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eHello,\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe Physics section of the docs should be useful reading:\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003ca href=\"http://urho3d.github.io/documentation/HEAD/_physics.html\"\u003eurho3d.github.io/documentation/H ‚Ä¶ ysics.html\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThere are RigidBody, CollisionShape, and Constraints and some good details.\u003cbr\u003e\nSeveral samples demonstrate the use of these, like \u003cspan class=\"bbcode-b\"\u003e19_VehicleDemo\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-b\"\u003e13_Ragdolls\u003c/span\u003e demos rig setups.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCollisionShape is independent from viewed models (but it can be constructed from them) and normally they are not rendered, but you can DrawDebugGeometry and samples demonstrate this.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThere are several simple, fast shapes like box, sphere, capsule‚Ä¶ SetConvexHull() constructs one from a convex Model‚Ä¶ SetTriangleMesh constructs one from a non-convex Model‚Ä¶ You can also make compound shapes.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:02:56.007Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":5,"readers_count":4,"score":6.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":791,"topic_slug":"how-to-specify-a-specific-geometry-is-for-physics-only","display_username":"Justin Miller","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"http://urho3d.github.io/documentation/HEAD/_physics.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Urho3D - Documentation - Physics","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":true,"admin":false,"staff":true,"user_id":21,"hidden":false,"trust_level":3,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":4337,"name":"","username":"devrich","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/d/ba9def/{size}.png","created_at":"2015-01-24T18:59:15.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI‚Äôve read over the Physics page before but after going through the RagDoll sample; some of the concepts in the Physics page make more sence now.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e[quote=‚Äúcarnalis‚Äù]‚Ä¶\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-b\"\u003e13_Ragdolls\u003c/span\u003e demos rig setups.\u003cbr\u003e\n‚Ä¶\u003cbr\u003e\nThere are several simple, fast shapes like box, sphere, capsule‚Ä¶ SetConvexHull() constructs one from a convex Model‚Ä¶ SetTriangleMesh constructs one from a non-convex Model‚Ä¶ You can also make compound shapes.[/quote]\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e‚Äúcompound shapes‚Äù That‚Äôs apparently exactly what I needed, many thanks! \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/smiley.png?v=10\" title=\":smiley:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":smiley:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\"\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBoth a RigidBody and at least one CollisionShape component must exist in a scene node for it to behave physically (a collision shape by itself does nothing.) Several collision shapes may exist in the same node to create compound shapes. An offset position and rotation relative to the node‚Äôs transform can be specified for each. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"carnalis\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n carnalis:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e‚Ä¶CollisionShape is independent from viewed models (but it can be constructed from them) and normally they are not rendered, but you can DrawDebugGeometry and samples demonstrate this‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDrawDebugGeometry ( \u003ca href=\"http://urho3d.github.io/documentation/HEAD/class_urho3_d_1_1_rigid_body.html#a237f7b27735f620d5e2b114a4027092f\" data-bbcode=\"true\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"\u003ehttp://urho3d.github.io/documentation/HEAD/class_urho3_d_1_1_rigid_body.html#a237f7b27735f620d5e2b114a4027092f\u003c/a\u003e ) ‚Äì This is something I think I‚Äôm going to experiment with to see what all  can get out of it, thanks for that \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=10\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:02:56.170Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":4,"readers_count":3,"score":0.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":791,"topic_slug":"how-to-specify-a-specific-geometry-is-for-physics-only","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"http://urho3d.github.io/documentation/HEAD/class_urho3_d_1_1_rigid_body.html#a237f7b27735f620d5e2b114a4027092f","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Urho3D - Documentation - Urho3D::RigidBody Class Reference","clicks":1}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":188,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"